\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]None is so fierce that dare stir him up: who then is able to stand before me?
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]Who hath prevented me, that I should repay him? whatsoever is under the whole heaven is mine.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]I will not conceal his parts, nor his power, nor his comely proportion.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]Who can discover the face of his garment? or who can come to him with his double bridle?
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]Who can open the doors of his face? his teeth are terrible round about.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]His scales are his pride, shut up together as with a close seal.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]One is so near to another, that no air can come between them.
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]They are joined one to another, they stick together, that they cannot be sundered.
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]By his neesings a light doth shine, and his eyes are like the eyelids of the morning.
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]Out of his mouth go burning lamps, and sparks of fire leap out.
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]Out of his nostrils goeth smoke, as out of a seething pot or caldron.
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]His breath kindleth coals, and a flame goeth out of his mouth.
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]In his neck remaineth strength, and sorrow is turned into joy before him.
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]The flakes of his flesh are joined together: they are firm in themselves; they cannot be moved.
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]His heart is as firm as a stone; yea, as hard as a piece of the nether millstone.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]When he raiseth up himself, the mighty are afraid: by reason of breakings they purify themselves.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]The sword of him that layeth at him cannot hold: the spear, the dart, nor the habergeon.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]He esteemeth iron as straw, and brass as rotten wood.
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]The arrow cannot make him flee: slingstones are turned with him into stubble.
\*[SUP]29\*[SUPX]Darts are counted as stubble: he laugheth at the shaking of a spear.
\*[SUP]30\*[SUPX]Sharp stones are under him: he spreadeth sharp pointed things upon the mire.
\*[SUP]31\*[SUPX]He maketh the deep to boil like a pot: he maketh the sea like a pot of ointment.
\*[SUP]32\*[SUPX]He maketh a path to shine after him; one would think the deep to be hoary.
\*[SUP]33\*[SUPX]Upon earth there is not his like, who is made without fear.
\*[SUP]34\*[SUPX]He beholdeth all high things: he is a king over all the children of pride.
