\*[SUP]5\*[SUPX]Deliver thyself as a roe from the hand of the hunter, and as a bird from the hand of the fowler.
\*[SUP]6\*[SUPX]Go to the ant, thou sluggard; consider her ways, and be wise:
\*[SUP]7\*[SUPX]Which having no guide, overseer, or ruler,
\*[SUP]8\*[SUPX]Provideth her meat in the summer, and gathereth her food in the harvest.
\*[SUP]9\*[SUPX]How long wilt thou sleep, O sluggard? when wilt thou arise out of thy sleep?
\*[SUP]10\*[SUPX]Yet a little sleep, a little slumber, a little folding of the hands to sleep:
\*[SUP]11\*[SUPX]So shall thy poverty come as one that travelleth, and thy want as an armed man.
\*[SUP]12\*[SUPX]A naughty person, a wicked man, walketh with a froward mouth.
\*[SUP]13\*[SUPX]He winketh with his eyes, he speaketh with his feet, he teacheth with his fingers;
\*[SUP]14\*[SUPX]Frowardness is in his heart, he deviseth mischief continually; he soweth discord.
\*[SUP]15\*[SUPX]Therefore shall his calamity come suddenly; suddenly shall he be broken without remedy.
\*[SUP]16\*[SUPX]These six things doth the Lord hate: yea, seven are an abomination unto him:
\*[SUP]17\*[SUPX]A proud look, a lying tongue, and hands that shed innocent blood,
\*[SUP]18\*[SUPX]An heart that deviseth wicked imaginations, feet that be swift in running to mischief,
\*[SUP]19\*[SUPX]A false witness that speaketh lies, and he that soweth discord among brethren.
\*[SUP]20\*[SUPX]My son, keep thy father's commandment, and forsake not the law of thy mother:
\*[SUP]21\*[SUPX]Bind them continually upon thine heart, and tie them about thy neck.
\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]When thou goest, it shall lead thee; when thou sleepest, it shall keep thee; and when thou awakest, it shall talk with thee.
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]For the commandment is a lamp; and the law is light; and reproofs of instruction are the way of life:
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]To keep thee from the evil woman, from the flattery of the tongue of a strange woman.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]Lust not after her beauty in thine heart; neither let her take thee with her eyelids.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]For by means of a whorish woman a man is brought to a piece of bread: and the adultress will hunt for the precious life.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]Can a man take fire in his bosom, and his clothes not be burned?
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]Can one go upon hot coals, and his feet not be burned?
\*[SUP]29\*[SUPX]So he that goeth in to his neighbour's wife; whosoever toucheth her shall not be innocent.
\*[SUP]30\*[SUPX]Men do not despise a thief, if he steal to satisfy his soul when he is hungry;
\*[SUP]31\*[SUPX]But if he be found, he shall restore sevenfold; he shall give all the substance of his house.
\*[SUP]32\*[SUPX]But whoso committeth adultery with a woman lacketh understanding: he that doeth it destroyeth his own soul.
\*[SUP]33\*[SUPX]A wound and dishonour shall he get; and his reproach shall not be wiped away.
\*[SUP]34\*[SUPX]For jealousy is the rage of a man: therefore he will not spare in the day of vengeance.
\*[SUP]35\*[SUPX]He will not regard any ransom; neither will he rest content, though thou givest many gifts.
